<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-535-892  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 535 892.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Graphics World  August 1989 v12 n8 p49(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Diagnostic imaging breaks the 2D barrier. (medical use of 3Dimaging)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Killmon, Peg; Kiely, Tom.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Three-dimensional graphics are growing in popularity as a medicaldiagnostic tool.andP;  Three-dimensional images seldom add newinformation; instead, they allow radiologists to communicate theirdiagnoses more clearly to other medical professionals and thepatients themselves.andP;  For example, three-dimensional images of abrain can be used to better plan surgery, instead of having theradiologist explain a two-dimensional X-ray to a neurosurgeon.andO;Other programs are used to plan heart surgery and plastic surgery.andO;The most important factor influencing the acceptance ofthree-dimensional imaging technology is the willingness ofthird-party carriers such as Blue Shield to pay for its use.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Three-Dimensional GraphicsApplicationsGraphics SoftwareMedical Diagnosis.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>